# TUI Rendering Rules

## Buffer-Before-Clear (ARCHITECTURAL INVARIANT)

Never clear the screen unless the render buffer already contains everything that needs to appear next. Every screen clear must be immediately followed by a flush of the complete next frame in a single `[Console]::Write()` call.

```powershell
# CORRECT — buffer first, then atomic clear+flush
Write-MainFrame -Force:$true -Date $date -NoFlush
Flush-Buffer -ClearFirst   # ESC[2J + full frame in one write
```

## Write-Buffer / Flush-Buffer / Clear-Buffer

- `Write-Buffer` — queue positioned, colored text segments (X/Y of -1 = continue from last position)
- `Flush-Buffer` — build VT100 string and output with single `[Console]::Write()`. `-ClearFirst` prepends `ESC[2J` + `ESC[3J`
- `Clear-Buffer` — discard queued segments without writing

## The `-DeferFlush` Pattern

When a dialog reopens on top of a freshly redrawn main frame:
1. `Write-MainFrame -Force -NoFlush` (buffer main frame)
2. Dialog adds its content to the same buffer
3. `Flush-Buffer -ClearFirst` paints everything atomically

## Cursor Visibility

Track via `$script:CursorVisible` (boolean), control with VT100 sequences. Never use `[Console]::CursorVisible`.

## What NOT to Route Through the Buffer

- Debug/diagnostic file logging (`Out-File`)
- One-off `Write-Host` calls during init (before main loop)
- `[Console]::SetCursorPosition` for dialog text input cursor (after Flush-Buffer)

## `Reset-PostDialogState`

Does NOT call `clear-host` or `[Console]::Clear()`. Only sets `$SkipUpdate`, `$forceRedraw`, and refreshes `$oldWindowSize`/`$OldBufferSize`.

## After `[Console]::Clear()` or `clear-host`

Always call `Restore-ConsoleInputMode` — these calls strip `ENABLE_MOUSE_INPUT`.
